{{For|the Hungarian pianist and composer|Rafael Joseffy}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}
{{Infobox person | image = Freud_aka_Joseffy_1908.pdf | image_size = | alt = | caption = Frontispiece, "The Marvelous Creations of Joseffy" (1908) | name = Joseffy | birth_name = Josef P. Freud | known_for = [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] | birth_place = [[Vienna]], Austria | birth_date = 3 March 1873 | occupation = [[Illusionist|magician]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1946|05|26|1873|03|03|df=yes}} | death_place = San Antonio, Texas }}
'''Josef P. Freud''' (also known as Joseffy) (3 March 1873 – 26 May 1946) was a [[Vienna|Viennese]] [[Illusionist|magician]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimsteinmeyer.com/newsletter/archive/fall03.html|title=Jim Steinmeyer newsletter Fall 2003}}</ref> {{anchor|Biography|History}} ==Life== Joseffy came to the United States of America at the age of 19 where he worked at a Chicago Magic Store, building props and [[Magic (illusion)|illusions]]. He invented a self-contained, no-thread version of The Rising Cards that astounded magicians of his day.<ref name=nook>{{cite web |url=http://www.magicnook.com/forum/bioHIJ.htm |title=Biographies Page H–I–J}}</ref> One of his mechanical creations was "Balsamo, the [[Brazen head|Living Skull]]".<ref>{{cite book|author=David Phelps Abbott|title=The Marvelous Creations of Joseffy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nt43AQAAIAAJ|year=1908|publisher=Open Court Publishing Company|page=7}}; Peabody, J. L. 'Spirit Pictures and a Speaking Skull.' ''Popular Mechanics Magazine.''39:6 pp. 817-820.</ref>
Joseffy was a performer at [[Coney Island]] as the [[Chautauqua]] & [[Lyceum]] headliner, and also played violin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.floraco.com/lyceum/ |title=Chautauqua & Lyceum Magicians}}</ref>
The American poet [[Carl Sandburg]] wrote a promotional booklet entitled simply ''Joseffy'' (1910).<ref name=nook />
Joseffy eventually stopped performing and became an electrical engineer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geniimagazine.com/wiki/index.php/Joseffy |title=Joseffy MagicPedia entry}}</ref>
== Literature == * ''The Marvelous Creations of Joseffy'' by [[David Abbott (magician)|David Abbott]] (1908)
Being very secretive about his inventions, it's been stated that in his book, ''The Marvelous Creations of Joseffy'' by David P. Abbott (1908), he either faked the photographs or showed apparatus that he did not actually use in the tricks to mislead the readers to the genuine secrets.
