{{Unsourced|date=April 2018}} {{for|the metro station in Buenos Aires|Los Incas/Parque Chas (Buenos Aires Metro)}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Los Incas | alias = {{flatlist| * El Inca * Urubamba}} | image = Jorge Milchberg.jpg | caption = Jorge Milchberg in [[Buenos Aires]] on 2 November, 2014 | image_size = 250 | landscape = yes | background = group_or_band | years_active = 1956–Present | associated_acts = [[Simon and Garfunkel]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Uña Ramos]] | genre = {{flatlist| *[[Andean music]]}} | occupation = Musician | origin = [[Paris]], France }}
'''Los Incas''', also known as '''Urubamba''', are an [[Andean music|Andean]] [[folk music]] group formed in [[Paris]] in 1956. Argentinian musician [[Jorge Milchberg]] (born 5 September 1928) is credited as the founder of Los Incas (as "El Inca", later known as [[Urubamba (band)|Urubamba]]).{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
They are best known in [[North America]] for accompanying [[Simon and Garfunkel]] on the song "[[El Cóndor Pasa (song)|El Cóndor Pasa (If I Could)]]" written by [[Daniel Alomía Robles]], [[Paul Simon]] and Jorge Milchberg included on the duo's fifth album, ''[[Bridge Over Troubled Water]]''.
Later on, they provided accompaniment on "[[Duncan (Paul Simon song)|Duncan]]", featured on Simon's first solo album ''[[Paul Simon (album)|Paul Simon]]'', and toured with Simon (as Urubamba) in the early seventies, appearing on the ''[[Live Rhymin']]'' album and releasing a pair of albums under their new name. In later years, they reverted to their original name of Los Incas and released several more albums on the French [[Buda Musique|Buda Records]] label.
==Members== * Jorge Milchberg — [[charango]] * Rob Yaffee — [[cello]] * Olivier Milchberg — [[Classical guitar|guitar]], [[quena]] * Lupe Vega — [[Singing|vocals]] * Juan Dalera — [[quena]] * Moises Arnaiz — [[Classical guitar|guitar]] * Jorge Transante — [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]
==Discography== * ''Chants et Danses d'Amérique Latine'', 1956 * ''L'Amérique du Soleil'', 1960 * ''Terres de Soleil'', 1962 * ''Amérique Latine'', 1964 * ''Special Danse'' (EP), 1965 * ''Bolivie'', 1965 * ''Pérou'', 1965 * ''Succés Originaux'', 1967 * ''Le Rapace'' (EP), 1967 * ''Los Incas'', 1968 * ''Inedits'', 1969 * ''El Cóndor Pasa'', 1970 * ''El Viento'', 1971 * ''Special Danse'' (EP 2), 1972 * ''La Fiesta'', 1973 * ''Urubamba'' (as Urubamba), 1974 * ''Río Abierto'', 1977 * ''Faszination des Südens - Doppel Star'' (with [[Facio Santillan]]), 1981 * ''Un Pedazo de Infinito'' (as Urubamba), 1982 * ''La Porte du Silence'', 1990 * ''La Plume de l'Oeuf'', 1991 * ''From the Other Side of the Volcano'', 1992 * ''Los Incas en Concert'', 2000 (Live Album) * ''El Último'', 2002 * ''Salvados del Olvido'', 2011
